Here's an example of blocking read interrupted by signal, with EINTR handling:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/stat.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <signal.h>

#define BUF_SIZE 1024

void handle_signal(int signum) {
    printf("Signal received: %d\n", signum);
    exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
}

int main() {
    int fd;
    char *buf = malloc(BUF_SIZE);
    struct stat stat_buf;
    ssize_t num_read;

    if ((fd = open("file.txt", O_RDONLY)) == -1) {
        perror("open");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    if (fstat(fd, &stat_buf) == -1) {
        perror("fstat");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    if (signal(SIGINT, handle_signal) == SIG_ERR) {
        perror("signal");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    while ((num_read = read(fd, buf, BUF_SIZE)) > 0) {
        printf("Read %zd bytes: %s\n", num_read, buf);
    }

    if (num_read == -1) {
        if (errno == EINTR) {
            printf("Read interrupted by signal\n");
        } else {
            perror("read");
            exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
        }
    }

    free(buf);
    close(fd);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we use the `read()` function to read data from a file. We also use the `signal()` function to handle the `SIGINT` signal, which is generated when the user presses the `Ctrl+C` key combination.

When the `SIGINT` signal is received, the `handle_signal()` function is called, which simply prints a message indicating that the signal has been received, and then exits the program.

In the main loop of the program, we use the `read()` function to read data from the file. If the `read()` function is interrupted by the `SIGINT` signal, the `EINTR` error code is set, and the `read()` function returns a value of `-1`.

In our example, we check the return value of the `read()` function to see if it was interrupted by the `SIGINT` signal. If it was, we print a message indicating that the `read()` function was interrupted by the `SIGINT` signal.

