Here's an example of how you can use the `pcntl` extension to manage the maximum number of running coroutines:

```php
<?php

// Enable the pcntl extension
extension_loaded('pcntl') or die('pcntl extension not loaded');

// Define the maximum number of running coroutines
$max_coroutines = 5;

// Define the coroutine function
function coroutine($data) {
    // Do some work with the data
    // ...

    // Yield the coroutine
    yield;
}

// Define the main function
function main() {
    // Initialize the number of running coroutines
    $running_coroutines = 0;

    // Loop through the data
    foreach ($data as $item) {
        // Check if the maximum number of running coroutines has been reached
        if ($running_coroutines >= $max_coroutines) {
            // Wait for a coroutine to finish
            pcntl_signal_dispatch(SIGCHLD);
        }

        // Start a new coroutine
        $coroutine = coroutine($item);
        $running_coroutines++;

        // Wait for the coroutine to finish
        pcntl_signal_dispatch(SIGCHLD);
    }

    // Wait for all running coroutines to finish
    while ($running_coroutines > 0) {
        pcntl_signal_dispatch(SIGCHLD);
    }
}

// Run the main function
main();

?>
```

In this example, we define a maximum number of running coroutines (`$max_coroutines = 5;`), and a coroutine function (`function coroutine($data) { ... }`).

We then define a main function (`function main() { ... }`) that initializes the number of running coroutines (`$running_coroutines = 0;`), loops through the data, and starts a new coroutine for each item in the data.

The main function also checks if the maximum number of running coroutines has been reached (`if ($running_coroutines >= $max_coroutines) { ... }`), and waits for a coroutine to finish (`pcntl_signal_dispatch(SIGCHLD);`).

Finally, the main function waits for all running coroutines to finish (`while ($running_coroutines > 0) { ... }`), and then exits.

