Here's a recursive JavaScript function that retries a request 3 times before it resolves the promise:

```javascript
function retryRequest(url, retries = 3) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
    xhr.open('GET', url);
    xhr.onerror = () => {
      if (retries > 0) {
        retries--;
        retryRequest(url, retries);
      } else {
        reject(new Error('Request failed after 3 retries.'));
      }
    };
    xhr.send();
  });
}
```

This function takes two arguments: `url` (the URL to request) and `retries` (the number of times to retry the request, defaulting to 3). It returns a promise that resolves when the request is successful, or rejects with an error message if the request fails after 3 retries.

To use this function, simply call it with the URL you want to request, like this:

```javascript
retryRequest('https://example.com/api/data')
  .then(response => {
    console.log(response);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
  });
```

This will make a GET request to the URL "https://example.com/api/data", and retry the request 3 times if it fails. If the request is successful, the response will be logged to the console. If the request fails after 3 retries, an error message will be logged to the console.

